{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"body":"Plan-review triage (round 5 PASS, signed; residual advisories judged non-actionable with justification per gate protocol):\n- P6 (0.4, recurring identical finding id since round 1): DET shape heuristic on 'and'-bundled criterion lines. ACs were split across rounds 2-5; the remaining bundles are semantically atomic (one test with parametrized default/explicit-False variants; a dated note per ADR). Further splitting reduces readability without adding verifiability.\n- T8 (0.0, rising_floor.py:86 section comment): already IN SCOPE of the plan as written — the What section makes the grep rule normative ('the enumeration is informative; the grep rule is normative, covering residuals') and this hit matches 'inert.*default'. It will be updated by the sweep.\n- G6 (0.0, rationale for superseding the discriminates_novelty eval): recorded here — the eval guarded against a non-discriminating novelty signal causing wrongful drops; that risk is bounded because the floor is fail-safe (any reader/hash/novelty error -> zero drops), precision-first (T_novel 0.7; priority floor 0.4 = corpus p40 'below major'), drops ONLY novel+low-priority findings in the advisory bucket (never blocking findings), and has a trivial total back-out (explicit false). Meanwhile the measured cost of running un-floored is high (32% verdict instability on identical plans; 95% of remediation edits mint new findings; 60% of gate compute in the 4+-round tail — and this very ticket took 5 rounds for a 2-line config flip). The operator explicitly authorized default-ON on this evidence; the eval remains available to re-run before flag REMOVAL (ticket 49ae-258b-4534-4d83)."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1783834388323296001,"uuid":"de7f77f8-e62e-4a79-a09b-a07675fca293"}